8%) of the responses had no identifiable address. There are no hard number breakdowns provided of the actual responses to the consultation questions, yet seemingly firm conclusions about responses are presented as facts. There is also no hard number breakdown of question response by responder address, town or postcode, making any demographic analysis of responses highly questionable. There are no hard numbers or graphical data provided to support the various “Key Outcomes” statements</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">15th February 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Agents acting for the DfE and SSET submit Planning Application 13/00271/FUL to South Bucks District Council for ‘Change of use of site from Offices (Class B1a) to a non-residential institution (Class D1) for use as a secondary school incorporating caretaker’s residence. Extensions to existing building and erection of ancillary buildings, together with alterations to the landscaping and access</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">16th February 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The Rt Hon Dominic Grieve MP attends a packed public meeting at Stoke Poges School to answer questions and issues raised by residents. In particular regarding planning concerns, Mr Grieve advises residents that “clearly as far as planning is concerned it is a matter for the District Council”</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">14</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> March 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> SPPC Public Meeting is held at Stoke Poges Village hall to which SSET and Mr. Kandola and SSET are invited to answer questions posed by residents. However, at short notice SSET decide not to participate and fail to attend the very meeting that had been set-up specifically in response to their request to address Village residents</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Stoke Poges Primary School conducts a survey of to assess the level of demand for places at KSA if it were to open in the village. Over 95% responded that they would not send their children, including a high proportion of Sikh families with children at Stoke Poges Primary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">April 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Lord Nash states ”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Neither the Education Funding Agency nor the Trust are circumventing planning rules; a planning application was submitted on 15</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> February 2013. It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">is now for those considering the planning application, in this case South Bucks District Council, to determine whether Pioneer House is a suitable location for a school”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">26</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> April 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Senior representatives of the DfE meet with SPPC representatives and local residents</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">15</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> May 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The responsible planning officer at SBDC issues his pre-committee report, recommending refusal on 5 robust counts. He notes that he has received over 850 letters of opposition</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">21</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> May 2013</span><span style="fo